 and moral issues in her own voice. Her three public orations and almost all of her letters, translated into English, are presented here for the first time.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAuthors, Latin (Medieval and modern). 0aFedele, Cassandra. 0aFeminists. 0aHumanists. 0aLiterature. 0aSpeeches, addresses, etc., Latin (Medieval and modern). 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / General.2bisacsh  aearly modern european literature, lit criticism, 15th century, female authors, women writers, venice, italy, cultural icon, king of france, milan naples, scholarship, renaissance period, pope alexander vi, queen isabella, ferdinand, spain, world leaders, letters, correspondence, epistulary writing, pen pals, independent woman, middle class, moral issues, ethics, social commentary, public orations, politics, history, political figures.1 aKing, Magaret L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRabil, Albert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRobin, Diana.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022623931640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226239330423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226239330/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles